INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '63d164f0-8882-43b1-a5f7-72d8fb7475bf',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$IPFS + ethers.js: Event Listening for Smart Contract Interactions$escape$,
  $escape$When interacting with IPFS-hosted smart contracts using ethers.js, you'll often need to listen for events emitted by the contract. ethers.js provides the `EventEmitter` class to handle event listeners. To create an event listener, use the `on()` method, passing the event name and a callback function. For example, to listen for the `Transfer` event on an Ethereum contract hosted on IPFS, use the following code: `const provider = new ethers.providers.IpfsInfuraProvider(); const contract = new ethers.Contract('ipfs://...'); contract.events.Transfer().on('data', (event) => { console.log(event); });`. The `on()` method returns an event listener that can be removed using the `off()` method.$escape$,
  $escape$const provider = new ethers.providers.IpfsInfuraProvider();
const contract = new ethers.Contract('ipfs://...');
contract.events.Transfer().on('data', (event) => {
  console.log(event);
});$escape$,
  $escape$typescript$escape$,
